node.text: The 2021 Apple iMac is an all-in-one desktop that is powerful, yet pretty. It's lightweight and colorful, and once you plug it in you are ready to go. Tap the link in our bio to read the full review.

node.title: Apple's Colorful New iMac Pairs Beauty With Brawn

Across 15 eastern states, the same ritual is underway. Billions of cicadas are emerging this week from Brood X—a population of three separate species (two from the genus Magicicada) that emerge from the ground at the same time. There are a dozen broods of 17-year cicadas and three broods of 13-year cicadas in the eastern US, each appearing in different years. But why are #cicadas so freakin' loud? Entomologist Samuel Ramsey has the answers.

Watch the full video at www.youtube.com/WIRED

node.text: On August 12, 1981, the great grandfather of the computers we all know today was born: the IBM Personal Computer. While IBM loomed large before the 1980s in business systems, the company's foray into personal computing changed the market forever.

node.text:
An alarming new report that includes 14,000 pieces of scientific literature paints a devastating picture of the path forward when it comes to climate change. It’s a full-throated declaration of what scientists know about how humanity has set the planet on fire: How hot it’s gotten and how hot it’s going to get, how much polar ice is melting, how droughts and storms are worsening, and how dire the path forward looks—unless we take drastic and immediate steps to stop loading the atmosphere with carbon. 

Read more about the findings of the report at the link in the bio.

Every time you go online, the terms you search, the links you click on, and the decisions you make are being logged and tracked in all manner of ways. Here's how you can cover some of those tracks—and maybe even not leave any in the first place. Read more at the link in the bio. 

🎨: @elacey_creative

node.text:
Protecting the immune-compromised isn't just about social responsibility—it's the best way to keep everyone safe. It's about ending a deadly pandemic and not giving the virus chances to evolve. As Tara Haelle reminds us, "The uncertainty and uneasiness many vaccinated people have been feeling in the past week is what our family and millions of others with immune-compromised members have lived with for the past year and a half. Except the stakes are higher now for immune-compromised people, given how much more contagious, and possibly more virulent, Delta is."

Read more at the link in the bio.
